    "UNITS": {
        "PVpanel": {
            "Unit Description": "Photovoltaic (PV) panels are recognized as essential components of renewable energy infrastructure by converting sunlight into electricity. Their performance is subject to various design and external factors. For instance, ambient temperature directly affects the panel efficiency, as the elevated temperatures lead to decreased power output due to semiconductor material sensitivity. In addition, the output of a photovoltaic panel partly depends on the angle of the sun relative to the panel. The global horizontal irradiance (GHI) is the amount of terrestrial irradiance falling on a surface horizontal to the surface of the earth [in W/m2] and dictates the potential energy yield of PV systems. Irradiation values can be obtained from an insolation map or from insolation tables that reflect data over the prior 30–50 years. Moreover, part of the solar radiation reaching an object is absorbed and the remainder is reflected. The fraction of solar irradiation that passes through a PV glass determines the absorbed energy. Usually, the absorbed radiation is converted to thermal energy, increasing the object temperature. In this regard, the thermal transmission coefficient of a PV panel impacts the heat dissipation capacity, affecting the overall performance. Finallt, the temperature coefficient of efficiency quantifies performance changes with temperature, influencing the energy output.",
            "Unit Info": {
